segments.text: Toby, if you would, could you please give me your full name and tell me a little bit about your background, how you came to chemical engineering, and how you came to Texas A&M?
Right.
My full name is Philip, one L, Toby, T-O-B-Y, Eubank, E-U-B-A-N-K. And I grew up in central Illinois, a farming community.
Took a BS degree in chemical engineering from what was then Rose Polytechnic Institute, which is now Rose-Hulman in Terre Haute, Indiana.
And then I went on to get a PhD at Northwestern University in Evanston, Illinois.
And as I was finishing at Northwestern in what I believe was October of 1960, then I was looking for a job.
Yes, I was in chemical engineering.
Yes, my family were Ford dealers, both in cars and farm equipment.
And so my father, who was the master mechanic, wanted me to become a mechanical engineer.
So when I went to undergraduate school, I had the intention of becoming a mechanical engineer, but then I got
very interested in chemical engineering because of its diversity.
In fact, it seemed to cover most of mechanical engineering and a lot of other things.
So I liked the versatility of it.
And was there a pretty good aura, I guess you could say, surrounding chemical engineering at the time?
It was sort of involved, isn't it?
Yes, it was, and there were jobs and very well paid.
And Rose only had
chemical, mechanical, civil, electrical engineering.
They only offered four degrees at that time.
It was very small.
I graduated with 70 total people that year, so very small engineering school.
So this is October 1960.
Yes, and that's when I came down here on an interview trip, and I'd also interviewed at several other universities, and with Exxon,
But I came down, and I talked to Doc Lindsay on the phone, and I almost didn't come because Doc was sort of abrupt, and he said, young man, are you sure you're really interested in this job?
And what I really didn't know was the history, and that Doc had built up quite a good department during the late 40s and I think early 50s, and then had essentially lost the entire department.
And so he was.
really quite discouraged.
And so I came down, and what really impressed me was that I didn't stay in a motel or hotel.
I stayed at Doc's house.
And his wife, Grace, who was really a fine lady, cooked breakfast, and we had a really nice environment here.
I liked the fact that this was a small town.
much larger than the one I grew up in, but still a very small, very hospitable place.
And later after the interview trip, then Doc even drove me back all the way to Dallas airport to catch a plane back to Chicago.
So anyway, I was really impressed by the hospitality.
In fact, it was a very small department.
You didn't take the job.
Right.
I took the job here because I also thought the state of Texas had a lot of, a very good future.
And I thought A&M had a very good future.
And it did turn out that was right.
Did the military or whatever turn you off or on?
No, it didn't.
I had taken ROTC at Rose, where it wasn't nearly as serious as it was here at A&M, but I was used to that.
After I came down here, I actually became a scholastic advisor to the airports and dormitories here at A&M.
So I sort of enjoyed this atmosphere.

And I was very impressed because when I arrived, the Aggies were something like, they'd been like 0 and 11 in football, and they still had very high spirits and were still very happy and yelling for the team and all that.
So I was very impressed by that.
And so you arrived here when?
I actually arrived in the first of March of 1961, straight from Chicago.
So it took a while to get used to this place.
I had married in September of 1960, and my wife had worked for IBM in Chicago.
She was one of the first teachers of computers.
digital computers.
So we came down here and then she started teaching high school at Hearn, and we later had children.
When you arrived, your offices were in the old geology building.
That's right.
The old geology building.
At that time,
Petroleum Engineering had just moved out.
They had a new building, which was Doherty.
But we were in there with geology and all the rocks.
And it was quite an interesting building.
We only had hot and cold running water, though, for the research labs.
So it was quite a challenge to set up experimental equipment.
And it was also totally un-air conditioned.
as were most of the buildings at that time at A&M.
And so I first went out and bought a Frederick air conditioner.
And even though it was half of my monthly salary, I had decided I was not going to survive the summer without some air conditioning.
And Doc Lindsay, although he was originally from Long Island, New York,
told me I didn't need one, that if I just waited about two years, my blood would thin out and it wouldn't bother me.
But I thought he was wrong.
The sweat would run down my hands during the summer and onto the ink pen, and I found it very difficult to write, and it was also very difficult to really think.
What about your teaching?
Well, I was lucky, in a way, because I came in March.
And I didn't have to teach anything until the next fall.
But then it hit.
And in those days, we taught three and four courses a semester.
And I remember teaching as many as 15 actual course hours, and teaching four different courses.
We only had about 17 senior students, so there was just one section of each course, but there were really, I believe, just three or four of us teaching then.
Yeah, there were.
There was Charlie Holland, Doc Lindsay, myself, and there was... Don Harris was still in Ecuador.
He'd been down there a couple years, but...
Bill Harris taught, was teaching part-time, and so was Dick Davidson.
And Dick had been here a number of years, but he was still working on his PhD degree.
I think he finished that in 62.
So we were pretty thin.
We were teaching a lot of courses.
So we all had to teach about four courses apiece
to make all the courses.
Well, of course, Doc was a well-known character, and he was probably about one of the finest men I've ever met as far as
personality and honesty.
But he was also a character of first rank.
Doc had a walrus-like mustache, and in his younger days, he'd worked in a, I think it was a boiler factory.
And so Doc never got over the fact that he had to shout.
And even if he was right in your ear, he would
He would shout, and in those days, well, my office was right next to Doc's in the old, well, what's now the geology building.
And so if you left the window open, and we were all on the telephone, we didn't need extensions because you could hear Doc all the way out through the window.
And Doc was really a great guy to work for.
And he had a lot of really good personal skills.
He had a lot of famous sayings like, if you have fish to fry, go do it in person.
So if Doc wanted a favor from somebody over in the MSC, if he was carrying on a short course or something, he would go over and ask them personally.
And he was well known all across the campus.

it was very difficult to say no to doc lindsay because he as he put it it was just like christmas and if you go in there and you ask them something with big tears in your eyes doc's quotations it would be hard for them to say no and so doc was was very good at getting people to do things for him
It was really sort of like Santa Claus.
He just didn't want to say no.
Now, he retired in 64, I believe it was, and Charles Holland stepped in.
There was no search, as such.
In those days, you didn't do things like that.
In fact, I interviewed Holland, and he said, how about it?
He thought about it.
Maybe that one day, he said, okay.
Right.
We actually knew, I'd say, at least a year in advance,
We knew probably back in 63, because there were really no secrets with Bob Quincy.
He said, I'm going to recommend Charlie Holland to succeed me as department head, and it's all pretty well decided.
So that was all done very smoothly, and like you say, nowadays we'd spend a year and a half doing a full-blown search.
now that was a very nice smooth transition now and then the next big moment i guess now roman is growing rather nicely
I think there's some of that.
There's excitement everywhere.
I'm trying to say you are.
Back in, I believe, about 1963 or 1964,
Because when I first came to A&M, I did some research into plasma arc jets.
This is not blood plasma, but this is very high temperature ionized gas plasma.
And in doing that, then I came under some NASA grants.
And so I did research for NASA from about 64 to the late 60s.
And so, I mean, I particularly had some interest in the space program.
Yes, yes, we went down there usually once a year for a general NASA-type briefing.
But I don't think anybody else in the department was really tied to NASA.
You know, as such, there was more connections, of course, over in the aeronautical engineering department.
Now, the other big thing, of course, that happened was, 67 through 68 was when we became Texas A&M University.
We also admitted, we formally admitted women.
and we did away with the compulsory core during the first two years.
So there were really a lot of changes here, and we started seeing, we started almost immediately seeing a great number of women coming into the chemical engineering classes.
You probably wouldn't remember this, but in the material I've dug up, the first two women I see enrolled must have come about 1907, wasn't it Hannah?
Prescott, Eddard Batcher and Prescott.
Batcher and Prescott, I don't remember their names.
But they were definitely listed as sophomores in 71.
Soon they came in in 72.
And then by 1975, I had a note from Hollis that there were 20 of them enrolled.
I think we had a special enrollment in 75 before it.
20 of whom were women.
And of course, there were two of them who were out there.
Do you have any special recollection of the first women or anything like that in the program or graduates?
Well, actually, at least here, we had women as undergraduates long before we had any as graduate students.
And the first women here as undergraduates were, they were very distinguished because they were all Cracker Jack students.
They were really good.
And I remember somewhere around 75, I was giving an exam, and a guy
One of the male students said to me, Dr. Eubank, you should count yourself lucky that you never had to compete with these smart female students.
And I thought, that's right.
Now later on, then, as we had more women, and we're now about one third undergraduates of women, then it started to level out.
And we'd pick up women who were nuts.
such strong students, so they became more the average.
I imagine the early ones were really competitive, too.
They had to be...
Yes, they were.
Often, I mean, some of those earlier classes, if you looked at the very top students, the ones that were above, say, a 3.4 out of 4, they'd be half women.
even though women were making up maybe 20-25% of the class.
How about places in the market?
Was there any difficulties, or was it more just pretty much women?
Well, actually, they were much in demand, because the companies were trying to fill quotas.
And I guess one of our early students, probably not the first, I just happen to remember,
was a gal named Linda Gonzalez, who was A&M Beauty Queen that year.
One Linda?
Linda.
Linda Gonzalez.
And so Linda was not only strikingly good looking, but she was also Mexican-American female.
And so she was really fought after by companies to be hired.
She was also a very good student.
She graduated about 3.3 or 3.4.
She went with Chicago Bridge and Iron.
Yes, she did.
And I heard from her father maybe 15 years ago that she was still with them and had a very good career.
Now as the faculty now,
There have been a number of recent hirings about the training came on, and Harvey came in, and Anthony came in, and Anthony came in.
But it was a change of nature.
You moved in in 72, to exactly the big room.
Yes.
Let me first say, Leo Durbin came in September of 61, right after I came.
We really came about the same time.
But then after that,
Ron Darby came in, I believe, in 65.
And then in 67, I think both... Dan Hanson came, I believe, in 67, and I'm trying to remember.
I think Ray Anthony may have come that year, maybe a year later.
Yeah, I didn't know you were in 54 or 65.
I've been in 54 or 65.
So both Darby and Clem were in second, and you made it in 67.
Yeah, so there's quite a...
an increase in the staff about that time.
But, sorry, back to your... One thing, Holland apparently consciously, and I don't know if it was a consciously added policy, was planning to hire young people.
Yes.
And it seems to have worked.
Yes, that was a conscious policy, at least after I came here and was involved,
That was definitely our policy.
We were trying to hire young faculty.
We concluded that was
simply the way to go.
It seems to really work, because the department congealed, and people grew in the department, and you had a good 20 or 30 year stay in there.
Yes.
Because of that policy.
And I think about that, because a lot of times, especially in the modern day, the way you try to bring in some big top dog, the impact on the academic world is minimal.
I think you have to grow your own.
You really do.
I like that, the more I think about it, yes.
But, no, you're right.
That was a conscious policy.
And the Department of Supervision had a very strong sense of cohesion and identity, which is unusual in the life of the United States.
Life's very good.
Yes.
But that was wrong.
Yes.
But your question on... Yeah, two characters that I've tried to really put in place.
Mikey, who I think was brought in from...
Yes.
Dr. Mikey was here when I came, and he was the director of the cottonseed oil laboratory.
I think he came in under...
The Calhoun-Benson program, everybody needs to teach themselves.
Yes, I think that's right.
And I know he taught some courses.
He had all his degrees, I think, in chemical engineering.
He was a very pleasant man.
He couldn't walk well.
He had a very pronounced limb.
But anyway, he was a very pleasant person who was quite low-key and very easy to get along with.
But he didn't really play a major, I mean, I'd say he didn't play a real major effect on me.
That's part of what I said, yeah.
Some of the
Right.
And then, of course, Bill Harris interacted a lot, because he was also in Cotswold.
Yeah, he got drafted the same way, apparently.
Right, right.
Now, what about Wynarty?
Wynarty came in in, you know, about 1758, and came in and started controlling something, and then the next year got promoted to fourth professor of chemical engineering.
Yes.
Do you know anything about all of that?
Yes.
Well, Dick Wynarty was here from when I came in, and I've become social, first of all.
friends with Dick and his wife.
And like you say, his degrees are all in petroleum engineering.
And Dick had gotten his Ph.D. degree in petroleum engineering from the University of Oklahoma.
But his Ph.D. advisor was John Calhoun.
So that's
There was an original Calhoun-Linardi connection outside of A&M.
So after John Calhoun came here, then he later brought in Dick Linardi.
And Dick ran what was called the Activation Analysis Laboratory.
And we're just talking about the space program.
But Dick was in charge of a program

whereby they would bend a rocket to the moon, and then Dick's lab was in charge of designing a little robot that had a shovel on it, and it was shoveled up a little bit of moon dirt, and then it was going to bring it back here, and they were going to subject this moon dirt to activation analysis to get a complete chemical analysis of the Earth or the moon.
Okay, good.
That's a good story.
That's a good time.
Yeah.
So, Dick was very much involved with NASA, and had a great deal of research running in him.
Big laboratory, and Emil Schweikert, who I think is still head of chemistry over here, was his original really top scientist, because Emil was a chemist and knew all about analysis.
So, Dick had sort of gotten himself off into some things that were more chemical, and he
So later, I remember we agreed to have him as a professor in chemical engineering, because he needed a home base.
Okay, that's kind of what I thought.
Did he ever teach that?
No, I don't think he ever taught anything in chemical engineering.
He did teach an activation analysis course, and a number of our students, I think, took the course.
Now, and I think even Swiker appeared at one time as a professor .
Yes, I think so.
I think Swiker, because we tried to align ourselves somewhat with the activation analysis, it was... That's the synopsis.
Yes, they had a lot of research money, and, uh, and for when Ernie was quite politically powerful here at one time, and so, and frankly, we all
We got along very well with Dick, and enjoyed working with him.
Later, one of his sons graduated with a degree in chemical engineering.
Anyway, Dick had sort of a long history, and I think he's still the administrator down in Houston
Yeah, for the medical...well, it's the entire medical complex down there that Dick administrates.
He said not too long ago, he said he's in charge of finding parking spaces for all the medical doctors.
Well, good.
That really helped.
Now, one thing you really became involved in was the extension, forces, and we can't just talk forces.
Yes.
When I came in in 61, they had
had a program for about 10, 12 years with Dow Chemical in Freeport, where we went in and taught one graduate course a semester.
We'd teach it on Friday night from 6 to 9 o'clock.
We'd teach three hours, which would cover more than the three one-hour lectures here.

And then the students down there, all of whom had a BS degree already, the students could then gather in one course a semester, and eventually they'd get enough courses that they could come up here and finish off a Master of Engineering by spending one summer here.
But they'd have to take these courses for about two to three years, or get together enough courses.
And this program was going good.
And then I was to teach, I think it was transport phenomenon in the fall of 61.
But I never did, because Hurricane Carla hit Texas, I believe, in late August or early September of 1961 and almost destroyed Dow Chemical, at least put it under four feet of water.
So Dow spent the entire fall semester trying to dry out.
But then later, I did teach a number of times at Freeport.
And then, I'm not sure I have the dates all exactly right, but going into the 1970s, we greatly expanded this graduate extension program.
And we ended up at one time with five centers down at Freeport.
Texas City, where we taught for Monsanto carbide and American oil.
In the old Monsanto plant, we taught at Texas City.
And then we taught Texas Eastman at Longview.
Actually taught it in Kilgore Junior High School, which was pretty nice.
But that was all
Texas Eastman Kodak.
Then we taught at Corpus Christi for Salonese and Pittsburgh White Glass, which at that time was a major company in Corpus.
We also taught at Victoria at the Stroman High School, and we were teaching, it was all carbide, Port Lavaca plant, and DuPont
I forget the name of the DuPont plant down there, but it's near the carbide plant.
So we were very busy with this program for a while, and it had some very positive effects, because people would take a master's this way, and then they would decide they want a Ph.D. degree.
As one example, we
Never in those days could we get an undergraduate student from the University of Texas to come over here and do graduate work.
The good UT undergraduates were all sent to the north to the top ten ranked schools.
Well, under this program, we ended up with about three or four PhDs who were undergraduate longhorns who ended up with a PhD degree from A&M.
In fact, one of them is still a professor at Arizona State and is well known for some textbooks.

anyway we had some good people who uh once we went into the plants and started teaching them uh they decided these aggies weren't too bad and they ended up at a m for a phd degree i expected that that complimented it really did because yes and we would walk in uh like in the fall to dow chemical they would just have hired
probably 100 chemical engineers.
And they would use us as a recruiting tool, saying that Freeport wasn't the end of the world, and that they could get a master's degree by night school right there in the plant.
And we'd walk into a class that had 40 or 50 people, and their degrees would be from all over the country.
So we'd have everybody in that class.
And it was a lot of fun to teach them.
And we were, as professors, we were paid extra to teach those courses.
So we were reasonably well in the first, but it was sort of a blast.
When I first started, because I was still quite young,
I would just drive to Freeport on Friday afternoon, teach the class for three hours, and jump back in my car and drive back here.
I'd usually be back here by midnight or a little after.
But later I got to the point where I always stayed over because I couldn't face the trip.
And usually, well, with Corpus, what I did was, in those days I drove to Austin Airport and took a plane in.
Corpus was not really easy to get to, and it's about a five-hour drive, so it's a little far to drive.
But we all drove to Kilgore in Texas City, and I think, yeah, we all drove to Victoria, which is about a three-hour drive.
In the short courses,
And you were pretty much as well involved in both existing and short courses as well.
Yes.

Another job that Doc Lindsay talked me into when I first arrived was to take over the instrumentation short course, which was started, I believe, in 1946 here at A&M by bringing instrument companies up and having a
about a three-day symposium, involved both the users and vendors of instruments.
And later on, this got into a lot more of computer control and computer companies.
So it rapidly was becoming very high-tech.
But this was started by Doc Lindsay and some industrial people in 1946.
And later, Charlie Holland
and had gotten a job of being director.
And that worked quite well.
But then after that, because when I first came here, Charlie Holland was really doing everything.
He was handling all the odd jobs for the department.
And so Charlie was very glad to see me come, because I immediately got all the odd jobs at the department, including instrumentation and symposium.
And it was in quite a mess for that time,
It had been given to a PhD student for the last two years, and its enrollment had sunk to, I think it was 150.
And so one of my first jobs was to reorganize the Consultation Symposium, get the Industrial Steering Committee back together.
So I had that job for five years.
from 61 through 66, and we got the enrollment back up to about 450, and got it back pretty good shape.
And that's completely outside of my field.
I had nothing to do, and still don't understand process control very well.
And also at that time, I got Leo Durbin involved, who is in process control, and so Leo started handling the technical program for the meeting, which was
a pretty good job in itself.
But that's still going on strong, and they just met, I think it was last week.
It's always in January, usually in the middle of a snowstorm or a sleet or something, but it's quite good, and people come from all over the country.
In fact, it's still the second largest instrumentation symposium in the world, next to the ISA annual.
It may have been.
I'm trying to remember.
I'll put you down in that so you can claim that thing right now.
I'm just wondering, to really kind of verify it before, if there's a note in the archive that was part of the faculty file that makes you get that.
And I'm not, you know, positive that there's a letter in the book that says that.
In other words, the South Texas chapter, that started early.
Oh, yes.
And you've probably run across the fact that the South Texas section of AICG, which was the largest, by far the largest,
section of AICG in the country.
It's now a powerful, dominant section.
The last two presidents of AICG are Texans.
Anyway, they are one powerful section.
But they were founded by Doc Lindsey Chalmers Kirkbride, who was then professor here at A&M, and a couple other people.
But the early officers, the first officers of the South Texas Section included, I think, Kirk Wright was president and Lindsey was secretary or something.
Well, but the student chapter here, I'm a little bit uncertain about, because, see, I thought that even when I first came here, there was a student chapter.
I know it bounced around, and like a lot of other organizations, it may have...
sort of died out, and we had to re-buy it.
But I'm not sure I want to claim credit for, you know, for really...
Okay, but you did become an advisor, right?
Yeah, I was an advisor at the time, and I may have sort of re-buyed it if it was, you know, not in too good of shape, but I'm not sure.
Before I forget, I'm sorry to interrupt, but there was one thing I should make sure you get in here, because it's typical.
This was back in Doc Lindsay's regime, but just rung a bell, and that is that Grace Lindsay had a thing that she'd started right after the Second World War.
We had a lot of students here who, of course, would come back to our services, and they were married.
And so Grace Lindsay had a thing every year where she gave to the spouses of the graduates a diploma.
which was called the PhD degree, putting hubby through degree.
And this was held at her house every year with great fanfare.
And what Grace did that made this really such a great place for the students was she had socials for the wives of the students, I think two or three every semester.
She got to know them, and she provided a lot of support
for those student wives.
And of course, they were all Doc Lindsey's boys, and they still are.
And most of them will tell you they've never forgotten Doc Lindsey, because he really formed what we call now bonds with the students.
I mean, he bonded with every student here.
That's good.
I'm glad you mentioned about Grace, because she's kind of, you know, not very obvious of a term.
I felt like she obviously had to have some support.
And even I talked with you, and, you know, you didn't have to say that.
Well, Grace...
Her dad ran an iron shop for her.
He had four sons.
He had those kind of sons.
He did, and...
Well, I remember when I first came, it was kind of humorous, because at that time, Doc knew that his two oldest sons were turning out just great.
I mean, there's no question they were already on their way.
His oldest son was teaching school already down in Houston, and Jim Lindsey, his second son, had already set up shop here in Bryan as a GP.
But anyway, he wasn't too sure about Hugh and Mark.
He said, well, they're still pretty young.
And they both turned out great, too.
But Grace was really an exceptionally fine lady.
And Doc always said that any of his success was largely due to her.

And she was really the perfect department head's wife, because she was very personal, but also very laid back, and not at all pushy, and just a very pleasant person who worked in well with everybody like Grace.
Now, let me jump ahead to another question.
How did that impact on the rest of the decade ?
No, driving while so high, crude oil that high, did have some positive effects on our research.
People like the National Science Foundation started paying a lot more attention to petroleum-related research.
And they also started paying more attention to the engineering side.
They had previously been more, quote, scientific.
They are the National Science Foundation.
But they then became much more interested in applied research problems, particularly related
to petroleum.
So it did have some, perhaps, positive effects.
But otherwise, in the teaching, most of the mission here, it didn't, I wouldn't say it had dramatic effects.
That's good.
The market still remained strong in the 70s.
Do you remember any of that?
Yes.
Not very good, but there was a time in there, I believe it wasn't until maybe the latter 70s when there was some years in there when it crashed and chemical engineers then couldn't find jobs.
We've gone through, since I've been here, we've gone through two or three periods like this where it was actually difficult for chemical engineers to get jobs.
And this was after years of where everybody would get five job offers and could take their pick and it didn't matter if they were not too strong of students.
But we then went through some years where it was difficult.
And what we had to do as a department was to
usually go out and take about the bottom third of the class and get on the telephone and find them jobs.
And that's where our network of having so many Aggie graduates of this department really paid off.
Because we've graduated a fair number of people over a long period of time, as has the University of Texas at Austin,
And together, we have a lot of old guys out there that are in key management positions.
Can you identify any special ones that you've looked at?
There are quite a large number.
Now, when we formed the first Lindsay Lectures Committee, this was, I think, in about, say, 78.
It was two years before Doc Lindsay
passed away, but I'm just sort of reading off the letterhead here that has our committee members.
There are people like Bruner Barnes, who founded Barnes and Quick Company in Dallas.
Is there identification with their business there?
Yes.
Great.
That's perfect.
Are all of these former students?
Yeah, these are all former students.
Excellent.
And let's see, I kind of think...
Well, Paul Dicer is still very much active, and he's a retired vice president of Shell a while.
I might use that list in the book.
That might be, would that be okay?
Oh, sure.
Why don't I do that, and I'll just say these people, for example, are students who rose to prominent positions, and I'll tie it in with the implementation of the intellectuals.
Right.
And identify them.
